      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "There are several technical reasons why the scheduled spectral scan cannot be completed within the remaining 12% power window prior to the sleep cycle. \n\nFirstly, the high-resolution spectral scan requires a significant amount of power to operate the instrument's advanced optics and detectors. The current power levels are already critically low, and attempting to run the scan would put additional strain on the system, risking further power depletion.\n\nSecondly, the scan requires a stable and precise temperature control environment, which is difficult to maintain with the limited power available. Any fluctuations in temperature could compromise the accuracy of the data collected.\n\nThirdly, the system's communication equipment is also power-hungry, and attempting to transmit the data during the scan would further deplete the power reserves.\n\nLastly, the system's software and firmware are not optimized for low-power operation, and attempting to run the scan would require significant computational resources, which would be difficult to allocate with the limited power available.\n\nIn light of these technical constraints, entering Deep Sleep Mode is the safest option to ensure the integrity of the hardware and the successful completion of the Jezero Crater scan.",
